st prostitution; the emergence of eugenics; and, eventually, the implementation of "racial hygiene" policies. In Colonizing Sex we see how these struggles were driven by rhetoric consisting of cries for defense, liberation, and truth—emphasizing in every historical moment how the sexual body has been, and is, part of much broader currents in political, cultural, and social life.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aAsia. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh1 aFoucault, Michel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrühstück, Sabine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLefebvre, Henri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052023548940uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093667640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520936676423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520936676/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles